{{Infobox artist |name = Arcadia Olenska-Petryshyn |image = Arcadia Olenska-Petryshyn.jpg |birth_date = {{date of birth|1934|06|19}} |birth_place = Roznoshentsi, Ukraine |death_date = {{date of death and age|1996|05|06|1934|06|19}} |death_place = North Brunswick, New Jersey |nationality = Ukraine, United States}}
'''Arcadia Olenska-Petryshyn''' (June 19, 1934 &ndash; May 6, 1996) was a Ukrainian-born American artist, art critic and editor.
She was born '''Arcadia Olenska''' in Roznoshentsi, [[Ukraine]]. She left the Ukraine with her family in 1944, moving to [[Augsburg]] in Germany. Five years later, they moved to the United States, settling in [[New York City]]. She was educated at [[Washington Irving Campus|Washington Irving High School]] and went on to earn a [[Master of Arts|MA]] at [[Hunter College]], later doing post-graduate work at the [[University of Chicago]]. She married [[Volodymyr Petryshyn]], a mathematics professor, in 1956.<ref name=acuarts>{{cite web |url=http://acuarts.ca/pdf_boutique/Olenska-Petryshyn,%20Arcadia.pdf |title=Arcadia Olenska-Petryshyn |publisher=Alberta Council for the Ukrainian Arts}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.digifind-it.com/rahway/data/news-record/1988/1988-04-14.pdf |title=Ukrainian artist to exhibit in Clark |work=Ahway News-Record/Clark Patriot |date=April 14, 1988 |page=3}}</ref>
She worked mainly with [[lithograph]]s and [[oil paint]]. She exhibited her work at shows in New York City, [[Toronto]], [[Brussels]], [[Shenyang]], [[Kiev]] and [[Lviv]].<ref name=weekly/> She was an active member of the "New York Group", an association of Ukrainian artists and writers, and helped create the Association of Young Ukrainian Artists.<ref name=acuarts/>
Olenska-Petryshyn was art editor for ''Suchasnist''', a Ukrainian literary and cultural journal.<ref name=acuarts/>
In 1996, she was murdered by her husband at home in [[North Brunswick, New Jersey]] following an argument.<ref name=weekly>{{cite news |url=http://www.ukrweekly.com/old/archive/1996/199607.shtml |title=Artist Arcadia Olenska-Petryshyn found dead; husband is charged |work=Ukrainian Weekly |date=May 12, 1996}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.tulsaworld.com/archives/error-may-have-made-perfectionist-a-killer-beloved-wife-slain/article_6feadf49-4f49-560d-a54d-39158640c50a.html |title=Error May Have Made Perfectionist a Killer // Beloved Wife Slain; Professor Is Charged |newspaper=Tulsa World |date=May 8, 1996}}</ref> Her husband was later found not guilty by reason of insanity.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www-history.mcs.st-andrews.ac.uk/Biographies/Petryshyn.html |title=Volodymyr Petryshyn |publisher=University of St Andrews, Scotland}}</ref>
Her work is held in various public and private collections, including the [[Ukrainian Museum]] in New York City.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ukrainianmuseum.org/ex_091213petryshyn.html |title=The Gift of Art: A Major Gift of Arcadia Olenska-Petryshyn Paintings |publisher=Ukrainian Museum}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.annexgalleries.com/artists/biography/3847/Olenska-Petryshyn/Arcadia |title=Arcadia Olenska-Petryshyn |publisher=Annex Galleries}}</ref><ref name=acuarts/> and the [[New Jersey State Museum]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://ssristories.org/rutgers-math-professor-kills-wife/ |title=Insanity defense possible as prof denies slaying his wife with hammer |newspaper=Star-Ledger |date=July 9, 1996 |location=Newark, New Jersey}}</ref>
