{{Infobox Artwork | image_file= Fragment of a Cope with the Seven Sacraments HMB 308A-B.jpg | title= Fragments of a Cope with the Seven Sacraments | artist= circle of Rogier van der Weyden | year= 1463–1478 | type= Embroidery | height_metric= | width_metric= | height_imperial= | width_imperial= | metric_unit= cm | imperial_unit= in | museum= [[Historical Museum of Bern]] | accession= 308A-B | url= [http://www.bhm.ch/en/collections/historical-collection/ Museum page] }}
'''''Fragments of a Cope with the Seven Sacraments''''' refers to a 15th-century [[cope]] in the collection of the [[Historical Museum of Bern]]. It is part of the [[church treasure]] from the [[Lausanne Cathedral | Cathedral of Lausanne]] sent to [[Bern]] after the Protestant conquest of [[Canton Vaud]] in 1536. The cope can be attributed to a master from the Netherlands in the circle of [[Rogier van der Weyden]] and was probably executed in [[Tournai]] where van der Weyden had a workshop from 1432 onwards.
== Description == [[File:Weltliche Schatzkammer Wien (239)pano-new.jpg|thumb|left| Mantle of the Vestments of the Order of the Golden Fleece, [http://www.kaiserliche-schatzkammer.at/en/visit/collections/secular-treasury/selected-masterpieces/ Imperial Treasury, Vienna]]] [[File:Mantle of the the Vestments of the Order of the Golden Fleece, detail - Imperial Treasury, Vienna KK 21.jpg|thumb|left|Detail of the Mantle of the Vestments of the Order of the Golden Fleece.]]
The piece pictured is the hood. It depicts the [[Eucharist]] in the new tradition of the ''[[Devotio Moderna]]'' that arose in the [[Netherlands]] in the fifteenth century. The embroidery uses one of the most expensive of the Tournai embroiders' techniques, the ''[[Goldwork (embroidery) | or nué]] (shaded gold)'' technique in which the juxtaposed gold threads are more or less closely covered by silk threads. A famous example of this kind of work is the ''[[Mantle of the Vestments of the Order of the Golden Fleece]]'' dating from around 1425–1450 and now at the [[Imperial Treasury (Vienna) | Imperial Treasury]], [[Vienna]].
The cope was commissioned by [[Jacques of Savoy, Count of Romont]] and presented by him to the [[Bishop of Lausanne]]. The Coat of Arms of the Counts of Savoy is embroidered at the bottom and show that the work was made before 1478, the year Jacques of Savoy was admitted to the Order of the Golden Fleece, as it lacks the [[Order of the Golden Fleece | Collar of the Golden Fleece]].<ref>Campbell & Van der Stock, pp.536-40</ref>
== See also == * ''[[The Justice of Trajan and Herkinbald]]''
