{{Infobox person | name = Victoria Hochberg | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = Victoria Greene Hochberg | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1952|12|24}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/73/Victoria-Hochberg.html |title=Victoria Hochberg Biography at |publisher=Filmreference.com |date=1952-12-24 |accessdate=2014-03-14}}</ref> | birth_place = [[United States]] | death_date = | death_place = | alma_mater = [[Antioch College]], B.A. 1964 | occupation = Film, television director, writer | years_active = 1975–present | spouse = }} '''Victoria Greene Hochberg''' is an American [[Film director|film]], [[television director]] and [[television writer|writer]]. She graduated from [[Antioch College]] in 1964 with a Bachelor of Arts in History.
She directed episodes of ''[[Doogie Howser, M.D.]]'', ''[[The Trials of Rosie O'Neill]]'', ''[[Dr. Quinn, Medicine Woman]]'', ''[[Touched by an Angel]]'', ''[[Models Inc.]]'', ''[[Melrose Place]]'', ''[[Central Park West (TV series)|Central Park West]]'', ''[[Ally McBeal]]'', ''[[Honey, I Shrunk the Kids: The TV Show]]'', ''[[Sex and the City]]'', ''[[Cold Feet (U.S. TV series)|Cold Feet]]'', ''[[Tucker (2000 TV series)|Tucker]]'', ''[[The Chris Isaak Show]]'', ''[[State of Grace (TV series)|State of Grace]]'', ''[[Kitchen Confidential (TV series)|Kitchen Confidential]]'', ''[[Ghost Whisperer]]'', ''[[Notes from the Underbelly]]'' and ''[[Reaper (TV series)|Reaper]]''. As well as writing ''[[I Married a Centerfold]]''<ref>{{cite web|work=[[The New York Times]]|title=I Married A Centerfold|url=http://movies.nytimes.com/movie/24111/I-Married-a-Centerfold/details?gwh=82AB8CD8FFD9E824BA319703F0ED1EB0}}</ref> and four episodes of the series ''[[Me & Mrs. C.]]''
In 2002, she directed the film ''[[Dawg (film)|Dawg]]'' starring [[Denis Leary]] and [[Elizabeth Hurley]].
Hochberg has won two [[Daytime Emmy Award]]s for directing ''[[ABC Afterschool Special]]: Just a Regular Kid: An AIDS Story'' (1988) and the [[PBS]] television film ''Sweet 15'' (1990).<ref name="womenintvfilm">{{cite web|url=http://womenintvfilm.sdsu.edu/files/hochberg_flyer.pdf |title=A Conversation with Director/Writer Victoria Hochberg |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=2014-03-14}}</ref> She has directed music videos for the [[Eagles (band)|Eagles]] and [[Boz Scaggs]].<ref name="womenintvfilm"/>
