 work;<ref>{{cite encyclopedia | encyclopedia = Britannica | pages = 410 | year = 1910 }}: "The poem also contains the earliest known fable in Greek literature"</ref> number 4 in the [[Perry Index]]. | Ray Winder |- | Cecino the Tiny | Tuscany | A variant of ''[[Tom Thumb]]''<ref>A number of variants are given on the site [http://www.surlalunefairytales.com/thumbelina/other.html surlalunefairytales.com], including an almost identical telling, [http://www.surlalunefairytales.com/thumbelina/stories/littlechickpea.html ''The Little Chick Pea'']</ref> | Chris McEwen |- | Her Lover's Heart | India | The ancient story of Raja Rasalu.<ref>Given in less readable form in {{cite book | last = Clouston | first = W. A. | title = Popular tales and fictions : their migrations and transformations | publisher = W. Blackwood | pages = 186–195 | year = 1887 }} [https://archive.org/stream/populartalesfict02clouuoft/populartalesfict02clouuoft_djvu.txt archive.org], along with mention of some of the variants, including the account of a certain Madam Butler of Hackney Boarding School, and the ninth story of the fourth day of Boccaccio's [[Summary of Decameron tales#Ninth tale (IV, 9)|Dacameron]] which concerns the troubadour [[Guillaume de Cabestang]].</ref> | David O'Connor |- | The New Hand | USA | Similar to the Brothers Grimm's ''{{Interlanguage link multi|The Old Man Made Young Again|de|3=Das junggeglühte Männlein}}''<ref>[[s:The Old Man Made Young Again|The Old Man Made Young Again]], Tale 147.</ref> and to unofficial legends of [[Jesus]] current in [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]],<ref>Shah gives a similar tale, ''Isa and the Doubters'', in his ''[[Tales of the Dervishes]]''.</ref> this one takes place in Alabama.<ref>{{cite book |title= Gypsy Folk Tales|author = Francis Hindes Groome |year= 2005|publisher=Adamant Media Corporation |isbn= 978-1-4021-8627-1|page= 291|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=xm1HZ5833YYC&pg=PA291 |accessdate=}}</ref> | Mai Watts |- | [[The Master Maid